title: For Sale:  Colt Lightweight Commander Stainless Enhanced Don Williams work
postcontent:
I bought this Colt new in the box in 1996 from Bob Swanson out in Phoenix, AZ and paid $625 for it. It is from a run of 500 Colt made of the first factory Lightweight Stainless Commanders and part of their new-at the time- 'Enhanced' models. It came with a stainless steel Combat Commander slide and the 'teflon' grey frame. It had the awful duck bill grip safety and plastic trigger and MSH. It had the black rubber grips w/ Colt medallions and a cheesy 'wrap around' strip that I cut off. Without it they are super nice grips. It came with 2 Chip McCormick Shooting Star 8 round mags and I bought 1 more for it. I put 300 rounds through it and sent it to Don Williams at The Action Works. I had the 'reliability package' done, and He put in a Videcki trigger, set it to 4.5 pounds, installed an S&A beavertail and wedge MSH, and an Ed Brown thumb safety and hammer. Cost for the work in '96 was $335. When Duracoat came out I had the frame done in Blackhawk tan. I since have only put another 100-150 rounds through it for a total of >450 rounds. It wears the stock sights still. It has spent most of its life in my safe as my intentions were this would be my everyday carry when I retired from the PD. The very little I did carry it, it wore an Andrews McDaniels IWB holster. Since this is the only holster it has ever known, I'm including it in the sale as well as the matching double mag holder. It also comes with the smaller belt loop attachment (not shown) This is a $165 combo.
Priorities and needs have changed, so its for sale.
$950 ftf I'm in Louisville Ky. Will ship for $25.00

title: For Sale:  Awesome Cavalry Arms Desert AR-15!!!
postcontent:
This is a Cavalry Arms "Dark Earth" (we call that 'tan') polymer lower.  Cavalry Arms decided they would overcome any concern about a weak spot where the stock would mount onto a lower by simply molding the lower and the stock together for an extremely strong combination that is only a couple of inches longer than a collapsible stock in its shortest setting (which is not good for shooting from, so you just have to waste time extending it at least one position or you may as well be firing from the hip, IMHO).  It is also an extremely stable and durable lower/stock combination, providing more stability and therefor better accuracy than the collapsible stocks that tend to wiggle around.

The upper has the "Full Profile" barrel which doesn't have that weak spot (for the M-203 that you or I will never own or use) milled into it.  This is my personal favorite barrel, and it is a lot harder to find than it should be (everyone, and I mean EVERYONE is using the M-4 Profile barrel because they are a dime a dozen, literally). 

It comes with the Piccatinny Rail Adapter on top so that you can mount any optic that you would like on it.  I have ordered an A1 rear sight kit so that I can install it and you will be able to use either iron sights or mount an optic.

Also, it has a Dark Earth MagPul MOE handguard on it.  The handguard has two MagPul mini-Picatinny rails with Dark Earth covers on them.  These can be used to mount anything from a laser to a flashlight to the front of your weapon.  

The vertical fore-grip is a UTG-Leapers.  It has slots on the side for the addition of pressure switches, and the removable compartment on the bottom has room for 2 AA or 3 lithium batteries (as spares for whatever you need them for, flashlight, optic, whatever...). 

It comes with a Dark Earth MagPul polymer magazine.  This magazine comes with a dust cover that snaps on the top and keeps out dirt and other debris until you need to use it.  When the cover is not covering the top of the magazine, it can be snapped on the bottom so that it doesn't get lost.  

Finally, it comes with a black nylon G.I. sling with metal hardware.

For only $650, this is an very nice and extremely capable weapon.  If you have any questions, please let me know!

title: For Sale/Trade:  FEG PA-63 with extras
postcontent:
One FEG PA-63 with 3 magazines. One original mag matches serial #, other two are parkerized, and all work perfectly. Also have original cleaning rod, and a couple of manuals. All the work common to these guns has been done: Have done some polishing to smooth out the trademark gritty trigger; replaced the recoil spring to ease the recoil a bit; and have swapped the hammer spring to make the trigger pull lighter. Also including the Wolffe Gunsprings calibration packs. These are three recoil springs and three hammer springs of different strengths so you can adjust the pistol to your liking and your ammunition. I have one of each installed and am including the original springs as well. They are extremely easy to change even if you're not mechanically inclined. It works beautifully, though, so there should be no reason to change any of them. Also includes three replacement firing pin springs (they came with the recoil spring pack).

Fires the 9mm Makarov round, also called 9X18 mm. I buy mine from ammunitionstore.com, which is located right in North Canton, for about the same price as 9mm Luger.

Read the description of this Hungarian Walther clone on wikipedia here:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FEG_PA-63

Gun seemed to be in unissued condition when I got it, and I have fired about 200 rounds through it. It works perfectly and is far more accurate than I am and the trigger is very smooth, has a crisp break and a short reset. Bore is perfect. The importer mark is clean, and is on the slide and not the weird "dot text" under the muzzle you see in a lot of pictures of these online.

I'm selling it because it doesn't fit my hand very well. My "firing range buddies" seem to have no problems with it though. It is a great gun for CCW. Very accurate and reliable, and holsters are easy to find. Also, the aluminum alloy frame makes it very lightweight.

I would like $265 for everything, or trade for a CZ-82 with 2 or more magazines.

Must meet face-to-face in the Canton/North Canton/Massillon area. Feel free to ask any questions or make an offer.

title: For Sale:  Winchester U. S. Model of 1917 Enfield
postcontent:
I am offering for sale a U. S. Model of 1917 Enfield service rifle manufactured by Winchester.  This rifle is one of several purchased by my father and older brother from Sears & Roebuck some 45+ years ago when they were shipped to outlets in crates and could be had for a song – remember???.  To the best of my knowledge, this rifle has not been fired since it was purchased.  I am not a collector of these rifles, but I do shoot an Eddystone in vintage military rifle matches.

Overall I’d have to rate the condition of this rifle as very good when compared to many others I have seen.  The wood and metal show the normal battle scars of a rifle almost 100 years old.  I am not sure if all the parts are original.  I am not able to find a cartouche of any kind on the wood as I see on my Eddystone.  The barrel is marked with a “W” and “4-18” near the muzzle along with that little “winged O” symbol also seen on the left side of the action (see photos).  The bayonet lug is marked with a “W”.  The top side of the bolt handle is marked with a “W” and the bottom side is marked with what appears to be an “E”.  The magazine follower is not ground off as you often see in “parade rifles”.  I showed this rifle to some far more knowledgeable people at a recent vintage match and was told there is some muzzle erosion, but the “bullet test” showed the muzzle rifling to be good.  The rifling appears to be bright the full length of the barrel.

It is very tempting to take this rifle to the range to give her a run.  My Eddystone shoots very well and I have little doubt this Winchester will do the same.  If you have any questions please PM me and I will give you my phone number.

Photos at: http://s698.photobucket.com/albums/vv345/cjkostic/

PRICE: $750.00 SHIPPED and INSURED; $700.00 face-to-face
